      "title": "VIP Tiers and Add‑On Options",
      "content": "VIP tiers transform a standard ticket into an exclusive experience by bundling extra benefits such as priority entry, backstage access, or premium merchandise. When defining a VIP package list the tangible perks and the emotional payoff they deliver. For example a VIP ticket might include a reserved front‑row seat a complimentary drink voucher and a meet‑and‑greet with the performer. Present the package as a single price that is higher than the regular ticket but lower than the sum of the individual add‑ons because the bundled perception feels like a bargain. Use tiered naming such as Standard VIP Elite to signal increasing value. Offer a clear comparison chart that shows what is included at each level and the price difference. This visual helps the buyer see the added worth without having to calculate it themselves. To upsell, train sales staff to ask qualifying questions like Are you planning to bring a group or do you value premium seating? Then suggest the next tier that matches the answer. Finally, limit the number of VIP tickets per event to maintain exclusivity and justify a higher price point."
